Problem Set 2

Computational

Question 1

Using different methods to calculate distances between p{1, 2} q{3, 4}

Manhattan:

sum(abs(1-3),abs(2-4))
## [1] 4

Canberra:

sum(abs(1-3)/(1+3),abs(2-4)/(2+4))
## [1] 0.8333333

Euclidean:

sqrt(sum((1-3)^2,(2-4)^2))
## [1] 2.828427

Question 2

Using distance function in R to calculate distances between p & q

Store two points as an object -

points <- array(c(1,2,3,4), dim=c(2,2))
points
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    3
## [2,]    2    4

Manhattan:

dist(t(points), method="manhattan")
##   1
## 2 4

Canberra:

dist(t(points), method="canberra")
##           1
## 2 0.8333333

Euclidean:

dist(t(points), method="euclidean")
##          1
## 2 2.828427

As shown above, calculation from basic mathematical functions yields the same results as the distance function in r

Question 3

Different methods of calculating distances can produce rather distinct outcome. Depending on the domain expertise and research question, one might prefer one method over the other. For example, manhattan measure is effective in showing the absolute magnitude of distance, whereas euclidean can produce straight line distance of data points.

Download old faithful data from the web

data("faithful")

Use basic EDA techniques to present and discuss data

library(tidyverse)
## -- Attaching packages -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.2.1 --
## v ggplot2 3.0.0     v purrr   0.2.5
## v tibble  1.4.2     v dplyr   0.7.6
## v tidyr   0.8.1     v stringr 1.3.1
## v readr   1.1.1     v forcats 0.3.0
## -- Conflicts ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- tidyverse_conflicts() --
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
ggplot(faithful, aes(x = eruptions), binwidth = 30) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(x = "Eruption time", 
       y = "Number of observations",
       title = "Histogram for Eruption") +
  theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

The histogram shows eruption time falls between 0 and 6 minutes, and from summary statistics we know that the minimum duration for one eruption is 1.6 minutes, while the maximum is 5.1 minutes, which are not readily obvious from the histogram. Nonetheless, we are able to present the distribution of eruption time. In this case, observations are dense around 2 minutes, and again dense around 4-5 minutes range.

ggplot(faithful, aes(x = waiting), binwidth = 30) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(x = "Waiting time",
       y = "Number of observations",
       title = "Boxplot for Waiting") +
  theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

According to the histogram, waiting time for watching geysur eruption falls under the range of 1 and 100 minutes. Similar to eruption time, we observe two peaks in the distribution of data points, one around 55 minutes and another around 80 minutes.

ggplot(faithful, aes(x = eruptions, y = waiting)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm) + 
  labs(x = "Eruption time", 
       y = "Waiting time to next eruption",
       title = "Relationship Between Eruption and waiting time") +
  theme_bw()

As shown by the graph, there seems to be a positive correlation between eruption time and waiting time, i.e. as the duration of eruption becomes longer, the waiting time required to see that eruption increases. Moreover, data points are concentrated in the top right corner and bottom left corner, meaning that we recognize high density for observations where eruption time and waiting time are both short or both long, with a gap in the middle.

Question 6

Generate an ODI for the faithful data

faithful_dist <- dist(faithful_scaled,
               method = "euclidean")

Question 10

Fit HAC using single and complete linkage, render the dendrogram and compare clustering patterns

library(dendextend)

par(mfrow = c(1,2))

hc_complete <- hclust(iris_sub, 
                      method = "complete"); plot(hc_complete, xaxt = 'n', hang = -1)

hc_single <- hclust(iris_sub, 
                      method = "single"); plot(hc_single, xaxt = 'n', hang = -1)

As we can see from comparing the two dendrograms, complete linkage produces a cleaner clustering by using the farthest points for intra-cluster distance, whereas single linkage produces somewhat straggling clusters with distance representing distance between data points closest to the other cluster.

Critical thinking

Question 1

  1. It is important to make sure the underlying patterns are not random. We could repeat iterations from treecutting and inspect the assignment of observations to see if the pattern holds.

  2. We could use the Hopkins statistic to assess the clusterability. If the value of H is below 0.5, it means the data contains meaningful clusterings. We can also use VAT, by plotting ordered dissimilarity image. If there are dark blocks along the diagonal, there is spacial similarity among some observations versus the other.

  3. Both aforementioned techniques can be combined to double check the clusterability of a dataset. By coupling mathematically exploration with visual aid, we will form better informed decision on whether to pursue further this clustering.

  4. If we couldn’t find clusterability with existing dataset, it might be worthwhile to add or drop some input variables before we decide to drop this exploratory analysis of the dataset, if the current one we are using is a subset of the broader universe.

Question 2

  1. The authors use a collection of DNA sequence data as initial data that feed into an algorithm that calculate the similarity in DNA between victim’s strand of virus and the accused patient’s strand, as compared to control group, thus establishing molecular evidence through phylogenetic trees.

  2. While not following closely the step of assessing clusterability, in their phylogenetic analyses, the researchers in this case did make the effort to calculate maximum-likelihood distance in which large numbers of pairwise distances are computed, following criteria of parsimony. They also conducted many bootstrap replications to establish the strength of results.

  3. The results show that DNA sequencing data for HIV sequences are highly heterogeneous for both patient and victim samples. An extension could be looking at the types of virus that are likely transmitted from animal to human. This makes computational tools like HAC useful for forensic investigations of disease transmission, which is particularly relevant to the development of cross-section collaboration between bioinformation science and public health.

Reference:

Metzker, Michael & Mindell, David & Liu, Xiao-Mei & Ptak, Roger & Gibbs, Richard & Hillis, David. (2002). Molecular evidence of HIV-1 transmission in a criminal case. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America. 99. 14292-7. 10.1073/pnas.222522599.
